

Gmail Inboxing Checklist 
Source: support.google.com/a/answer/81126  ·  Google Email Sender Guidelines  ·  Effective Feb 
1, 2024 
SECTION 1 — ALL SENDERS 
Required at any volume 
  
☐ 
SPF or DKIM email authentication is set up for the sending domain. 
☐ 
Sending domain or IP has a valid PTR (reverse DNS) record that resolves to a 
hostname. 
The hostname must also have an A or AAAA record resolving back to the same 
sending IP. 
☐ 
Email is transmitted over a TLS connection. 
☐ 
Spam rate in Postmaster Tools is below 0.10% and never reaches 0.30%. 
Requirement threshold is 0.30%; best-practice target is below 0.10%. 
☐ 
Messages are formatted per Internet Message Format standard RFC 5322. 
Includes a valid Message-ID. Single-instance headers (From, To, Subject, Date) 
appear only once. 
☐ 
The From: header does not impersonate a Gmail address (@gmail.com or 
@googlemail.com). 
☐ 
If forwarding / operating a mailing list or inbound gateway: ARC headers are added to 
outgoing email. 

Mailing list senders must also add a List-id: header specifying the mailing list. 
  
SECTION 2 — BULK SENDERS ONLY 
Required if sending 5,000+/day to 
Gmail 
  
☐ 
Both SPF and DKIM are set up for the sending domain (both required, not just one). 
☐ 
DMARC is set up for the sending domain. Policy can be set to "none." 
☐ 
For direct email: the domain in the From: header is aligned with the SPF domain or 
the DKIM domain (DMARC alignment). 
☐ 
Marketing and subscribed messages include both one-click unsubscribe headers. 
List-Unsubscribe-Post: List-Unsubscribe=One-Click List-Unsubscribe: 
<https://yourdomain.com/unsubscribe/...> 
☐ 
A clearly visible unsubscribe link is in the body of every marketing or subscribed 
message. 
  
SECTION 3 — MESSAGE CONTENT & FORMATTING 
All senders 
  

☐ 
HTML messages are formatted per the HTML Living Standard 
(html.spec.whatwg.org). 
☐ 
From: header includes only one email address. 
Example: From: notifications@yourdomain.com — no multiple addresses. 
☐ 
Message subject, headers, display names, and body are accurate and not misleading 
or deceptive. 
☐ 
Subject line does not start with "Re:" or "Fwd:" unless the message is an actual reply 
or forward. 
☐ 
From: and To: headers include only actual senders and recipients. 
☐ 
Emojis or non-standard characters are not used to imitate graphic elements 
(checkmarks, badges, verification symbols) with intent to deceive. 
☐ 
No HTML or CSS is used to hide content in the message. 
☐ 
All web links in the message body are visible and clearly indicate where they lead. 
☐ 
Sender information is clear and visible in the message. 
☐ 
Message does not mix different types of content (e.g., no promotions in transactional 
receipts). 
  

SECTION 4 — DISPLAY NAME RULES 
All senders 
  
☐ 
Display name identifies the sender only — does not include subject line text or 
message content. 
Prohibited: "Important Update — From [Company]", "TIME IS RUNNING OUT (SALE)", 
"Last Chance", "URGENT REQUEST" 
☐ 
Display name does not include the recipient's name. 
☐ 
Display name does not imply a message reply or threaded conversation. 
Prohibited: "User (2)", "[recipient name] <info@org.com>" 
☐ 
Display name does not use emojis or non-standard characters to imitate graphic 
elements. 
Prohibited: "✔ LATEST UPDATE", "MAIL, ME ", "[1] New Message" 
☐ 
Display name does not use an @gmail.com domain as the display name for bulk 
email. 
  
Source: support.google.com/a/answer/81126  ·  Compiled March 2026 
 